Rating: 3
I have been eating corned beef and cabbage since I was small. My grandmother put the meat in the pot, covered with cold water and simmered with a bay leaf and onions. Later she added a quartered cabbage, carrots, turnip and potatoes. Once the meat is softer, you start adding the veggies. Adding what takes the longest to least in that order for cooking timne. The vegetables add to the flavor I think. I don't like to use the spice packets that come with the beef. When I serve, I strain and separate everything. We then put some of the broth over what we take, add a pat of butter and for me, cider vinegar! That does it. Oh, we don't trim the fat off either as it tastes the best! Not for the diet conscious, but just darned good and simple. The hard part is taking the hours to simmer it!!! Usually mine is done minus several carved off corners.... 8 ^) Also, my grandmother was English. No Irish here, I also make this several times a year. The meat will also shrink by about half size, so be sure to have plenty on hand. It's as simple as boiling water!

