This is answering the review - "What does the recipe mean by "freshly made mustard"? by graceross from Ottawa on 03/16/11" In the UK and Ireland, we often 'make up' English mustard from Colman's Mustard Powder and water. Just place a bit of the powder from that ubiquitous yellow tin in a small dish, stir in enough water so it becomes a creamy consistency and allow to sit for a bit (allows the mustard to absorb the water and 'firm up'.) English mustard is HOT and has a wonderful bite. Freshly made is nothing like the stuff from a jar. Try it. It's a world away from yellow French's or Gulden's spicy brown.

