My Irish-American mother,who learned it from her Immigrant-American mother taught me, or rather I watched and was allowed to peel the vegetables. When I was younger I learned how to corn beef as a butchers apprentice too. In those earlier/bygone days it was necessary to bath the pieces overnight in water in the fridge to desalinate it (cold water draws the salt out). Not generally necessary today I think. But always simmer the beef alone for three hours (very low simmer) with herbs and spices. And actually remove the brisket to cook the vegetables: potatoes and carrots for around 40 minutes, cabbage for about the last twenty. The broth is served on the meat and vegetables, and if your like me some more later in a cup. Don't leave every thing in the broth. It makes a mush and ruins tomorrows lunch. Don't cook it with mustard! Serve it,and ketchup on the side with Caraway seeded rye bread.

