I tried the method from this recipe last year and it ruined my corned beef! It was tough and inedible even though I simmered it at a moderately low temp on the stove top. Veg turns to mush as people say I won't make it on the stove top again. But........Here's what I did the second time around: This year I used a DIFFERENT METHOD suggested by some other reviewers and the results were much better! I braised the corned beef brisket in my Le Creuset cast iron pot with the lid on at a very low temp. {285} for 5 hours and it came out tender and eatable. I also used another tip from a reviewer, after the corned beef was done braising I put it on a cookie sheet fat side up and sliced part of the layer of fat off across the top leaving a thin layer of fat across the top. Then I spread spicy brown mustard over the fat, then sprinkled generously with brown sugar and put under the broiler for a minute or two. {you have to watch it or sugar will burn fast}. The results were delicious! I will braise it then broil it with mustard and brown sugar every year from now on. I also used some one's suggestion of adding beer so I used Yuengling Black and Tan,to braise it in. Bad idea because it made the juices and vegetables bitter.

