Rating: 4
OK-as Emeril would say, let's take it up another notch! This recipe is how I always cook it, with three slight modifications. First, I add small new (waxy variety) potatoes 45 min. before meat is done & I don't add the cabbage but wait till the brisket is completely cooked. Remove it & place it in shallow ovenproof dish. Place carrots & potatoes in ovenproof covered casserole & keep warm on back of stove. Cook cabbage (it only takes 15-20 minutes to cook-nothing worse than overcooked cabbage...ask Julia Child). Now back to the meat. Spread top (fatty side) with spicy mustard & sprinkle with brown sugar. Run under broiler for 5-10 minutes to crisp up the fat. Slice & arrange on platter surrounded by all those lovely veggies. I also agree with those who suggest including the spice packet & using beer/stout to replace some of the water.

Rating: 3
Good basic recipe. If you really want a fantastic addition to this dish, try this parsley gravy: Parsley Gravy " 1 stick of butter (4 oz / 110 g) " 4 tablespoons flour " 6 cups strained corned beef broth " ½ cup chopped parsley " Dollop horseradish " salt, to taste " pepper, to taste In a heavy bottomed pot or skillet, melt the margarine or butter. Sprinkle over with flour and stir to combine well with the fat. It will form a paste. Cook this over medium-low heat till it starts to brown slightly and smells nutty. Using a whisk, beat in a cup of strained broth at a time. Let the sauce come to a boil, whisking all the while. If the sauce seems too thick, add more strained broth. Season to taste with salt and pepper, and horseradish. Serve hot. I'm told it is also delicious with half buttermilk and half corned beef broth

