Rating: 0
Corned beef & cabbage is essentially the same as what is called a New England Boiled Dinner. It is similar to the ordinary, every day Irish dish of bacon & cabbage ("bacon" means a cut of preserved pork; here we might use shoulder or "picnic ham."). All these dishes involve boiled meats. I am puzzled as to why respondents here seem to be fixated on using a pressure cooker. Time aside, there is no need to use a pressure cooker. In fact, there is reason to not use one: Corned beef can be very, very salty. If you are not sure of how salty your beef is, because you have never had the corned beef of a particular processor/brand before, then you might need to bring the beef to a boil from cold, drain & rinse, and repeat. Alternatively, you would soak the beef in cold water for some hours to leech out some of the salt. Oh, to follow up from "nabarda from Austin": in the British Isles, Patty is female, Paddy is male. Both the spelling and the pronunciation are different. So, if you must shorten Patrick/Padraig, it is not Patty's Day, but Paddy's, as in "paddy wagon."

Rating: 0
for Solea, in the Philippines: If you google "corning beef, Julia Child", you'll get to a Julia recipe for corning beef, which I believe is the same as the recipe in her "Julia Child & Company" (1978). The JC recipe produces New England style corned beef, which is gray, not red. (The red corned beef has been cured with salt petre, not table salt.) It is very good, and it is not hard to do, but the meat has to sit in the brine for about 2 weeks. The most popular cut seems to be brisket, but round is also common. Corned brisket is often sold as "flat cut"--that is, only a couple of inches high and quite long. If you cook brisket, try to cut across the grain to get smooth slices: it may take a bit of cutting tiny slices to be sure you're choosing the right direction to cut in.

