We had this dish for our St. Patrick's Day dinner party this Sunday. I had bought a 2.50 lb.corned beef.(for 4 people) Using the pressure cooker method,(recommended by chefs who reviewed this recipe) I cooked the onions, mustard, beef and carrots for 45 min then turned off flame, let the pot sit until steam reduced after about 15 min then added a head and a half of organic cabbage cut in wedges and half a large bag of whole fingerling potatoes. Many more veggies than suggested. I recommend that carrots should be added in at the same time as potatoes (not earlier). I almost covered the beef with water but not quite . Lastly, I cooked the final ingredients for over an hour or more and let it sit, flame off, in the pot until guests arrived. Results were fantastic! The beef came out beyond delicious with perfect consistency and flavor. The potatoes were dreamy, smooth and whole, little wonders and just the right texture...cabbage turned to mush but was tasty like a creamy spread. Next time I would put the cabbage in quite a bit later which would mean a third opening and de-steaming of the pot. We served the beef with mustards of all types and Irish soda bread, baguettes, and even moist sweet ,cornberead made with creamed corn, etc.Also served a large broccoli, french green bean, romaine & hearts of palm salad. Broth from cooking was savory and salty and I stored it to use to heat up leftovers in. Dessert was a double lemon meringue pie. A very easy and rewarding dinner I will definitely cook more than once a year!

